        @{u}@{b}@{fg highlight}Major Rakal's Romulan Review@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}

        @{b}Major Rakal's Romulan Review #18@{ub}


Aefvadh! Now that we've all recovered from my back-to-back dilemma
reviews, I'd like to do a slightly different personnel review. It's not
exclusively Romulan, but the cards are similar and easy to review
together. Besides, this review is for a friend of mine, who hangs out on
various BBSs, newsgroups, and chat rooms as either of the EEHPs
(Emergency Engineering Holographic Programs), and actually plays with
them, too (and beat me with them more than once, I fear). Hi, K'Tomek,
here are *both* your alter egos...


    @{b}TOMEK@{ub}

    Common Romulan Personnel, universal

    Integrity 4, Cunning 7, Strength 6, Hologram icon

    ENGINEER: Astrophysics

@{i}"Re-creation of a male Romulan. Alien entity assumed this body in 2369."@{ui}


    @{b}K'TESH@{ub}

    Common Klingon Personnel, universal

    Integrity 5, Cunning 5, Strength 6, Hologram icon

    ENGINEER: Stellar Cartography

@{i}"Re-creation who assisted in the Age of Ascension ritual. Perfected
current pain-stick design for ritual use."@{ui}


These guys were somewhat frustrating in the premiere set. Both Romulans
and Klingons were mighty short on ENGINEERS compared to the Feds, and
one of each was a hologram, for crying out loud. And not a red or green
holodeck in sight. Short of a Husnock Ship or a Treaty with Starfleet,
the only way to play them was Holo-Projectors. And nothing so far makes
them work on an outpost. With the advent of AU, things got a *little*
better: each affiliation got an AU ship with a holodeck--and a hefty
staffing requirement. Question is, are they worth it? One red dot in
each skills box doesn't go very far. Can you get along without them?

First, the Romulans: five green missions (including a 40- and a 45-
pointer) require Astrophysics. Investigate "Shattered Space" even needs
Astro x2. The only other Romulan Astrophysicist is the unique Mirok,
with mediocre stats (lousy Integrity) but both SCIENCE and ENGINEER to
recommend him. He needs a backup (especially if you're going to try
Shattered Space), but from the start Dr. Reyga has been a lot easier to
use than a holo (and better than Mirok to boot), or Jo'Bril; with QC you
can also choose from Timicin (if you can time it right before he dies),
Data's Body (if you can get the head), or Paul Manheim. If you want a
universal ENGINEER, Palteth's Computer Skill is more generally useful.
So not much real need for poor Tomek.

Now, the Klingons: four red missions require Stellar Cartography, all 35
points or less. Two can be done alternatively with CUNNING alone--but
CUNNING > 50 is tough for the Klingons, with their average CUNNING of
only 5.5. What are your other choices for Stellar Cartography?  Dr.
Reyga. That's it. Except for a little addition in QC called K'chiQ. You
can only have one K'chiQ aboard your ship, and you have to make sure she
doesn't get caught without her warrior, and she needs an AU door (which
means she can be stowed on a Cryosatellite)...but she can deliver the
Stellar Cartography. You'll have to decide which is more trouble, the
care and feeding of K'chiQ, or keeping the Holo-Projectors operational.

So why might you want to use the EEHPs anyway? As redshirts, of course.
Sure, holograms can get "killed" by dilemmas. But instead of going to
your discard pile like normal personnel, they just deactivate back to
the controlling ship, and pop up again, good as new, on your next turn.
What's that, you say, Love Interests don't kill? Right, but try to send
a holo to the far end of the spaceline and he "leaves the holodeck" so
to speak...deactivated again. You don't have to go off and pick him up.
And a few dilemmas they're outright immune to; if it affects DNA, holos
(who don't have any) can just laugh at it. There are some wall dilemmas
they can't get by, of course, notably Shaka. And you do have to watch
out for ship-destroyers (about the only way to discard a holo). But you
*can* send off one holo after another to encounter killers, and have
them all come back to life next turn.

If you're going to try to use holos, the Romulans have an edge. First,
the other green holo is the surprisingly useful Jera (MEDICAL: Biology,
Youth); using her too makes generating holos more worthwhile. The
Klingons only have Fek'lhr (VIP: Honor, Treachery, 6-1-15), dim-witted
and of much more limited use (maybe handy for Brute Force). Second, the
Romulan holodeck-equipped ship, the Decius, with staffing requirements
of CSA (and you probably are using the good Major so there's your AU
icon), is a lot easier to use than the I.K.C. Fek'lhr which requires one
more AU icon.

The Major's Combos:

- K'Tesh or Tomek and the 2-Player Game Introductory Rules.

Oh, you wanted a *card* combo...

- Tomeks + Jeras + Decius + Study Lonka Pulsar

- lots of K'Teshes + Holo-Projectors + planet missions

Jolan tru,

Major Rakal
Tal Shiar

